<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-11-24T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-11-24T20:00:00-05:00" n="444" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d444">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/960.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-11-24T20:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 24, 1913—8 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In regard to your telegram of the 13th instant in regard to removal of
                            vessels, you are advised that the <hi rend="italic">Nashville</hi> will
                            proceed to Santiago de Cuba for about a fortnight and will be back at
                            her station in Dominican waters about the 10th of December, in
                            sufficient time for any service in relation to the election.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>